charcoal grills burn hotter than gas grills and you can burn wood in a charcoal grill, to impart a natural, smoky flavor to your foods.electric grills are another choice, and may be the only option for apartment or condo dwellers, but they don't impart a real barbecue flavor.while gas is a quick start option for fast grilling, charcoal infuses delicious smoky aromas into foods for an authentic grill flavor.generally speaking, it's smart to choose a grill with at least two separately controlled burners so you can grill foods indirectly (a technique often used for cooking larger items like whole chickens), a built-in temperature gauge, and a gas gauge, so you won't run out of propane mid-meal.stainless steel is the best (and priciest) choice because it holds up well to the elements over time.gas grills are convenient, they ignite at the push of a button and allow you to control the heat with the turn of a knob, but they're not ideal for true slow-cooked barbecue.inexpensive grills start around 500 square inches, and a high-end gas grill may offer several times that capacity.a small grill may have about 40,000 btus or fewer, while a large grill may have as many as 100,000 btus of power.it may be tempting to save some money by starting out with a less expensive grill that you can upgrade later, but that's not always a smart strategy, particularly if the grill is built-in.it's the most important feature of your outdoor kitchen, and a good place to invest a big chunk of your budget.if you regularly cook for a crowd, you may want a large grill with multiple burners and a smaller surface with three burners is fine for meals for a family of four.you'll find kettle grills, built-in grills, table grills, hibachis, barrel smokers, water smokers and ceramic cookers, all of which use charcoal to grill or barbecue foods.the right one for you will depend on how you like to cook, but whichever charcoal grill suits your style, look for these signs of quality: get tips on how to find 